[Student "S"]
{South realizes that to make a takeout double, then jump in your own suit you must have a very good hand. So he bids the game. North plays 4\H. East leads the \CK, which you take with the \CA.

You have four losers. If you are thinking about leading toward your \DK you are delusionary. East has the \DA and you know it. Your best hope is to end-play East with the \CT and force him to break the \Ds. 

Play one round of trumps with the \HA. You can't play any more because you will need an entry to dummy for the elimination.

Next play \SK, \SA and ruff a \S high.

Lead a \H to dummy's \HQ. East shows out. Play dummy's last \S. West is now void, so if he ruffs you over-ruff. Otherwise you ruff with a small trump.

Now throw East in (you hope!) with the \CT.

Fortunately East has to take the \CT. Since he has nothing left but \Cs and \Ds he must lead one or the other. A \D lead will give you a trick with your \DK and a \C lead will allow you to ruff in dummy (West still has a \C) and discard a \D from your hand.

Some problems are tougher than others, this being a tough one.  

It was not a complete elimination since West still had a trump when you threw East in. However, it worked because East was out of both \Ss and \Hs.}
[Play "W"]CK

